02384cam a2200385 i 20161228114441.0m     o  d        cr unu||||||||130926s2014    miua    ob   s001 0 eng d  a2013036410  a9780472119141q(hardback : acid-free paper)  a0472119141q(hardback : acid-free paper)  a9780472029716q(e-book)7 a10.3998/mpub.5470718  aMiUbengcMiU  an-us---00aJK516b.W377 201400a352.2309732231 aWaterman, Richard W.14aThe presidential expectations gap :bpublic attitudes concerning the presidency /cRichard Waterman, Carol L. Silva, and Hank Jenkins-Smith. 1aAnn Arbor :bThe University of Michigan Press,c2014.  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  aIncludes bibliographical references (pages 195-203) and index.  a"For decades, public expectations of U.S. presidents have become increasingly excessive and unreasonable. Despite much anecdotal evidence, few scholars have attempted to test the expectations gap thesis empirically. This is the first systematic study to prove the existence of the expectations gap and to identify the factors that contribute to the public's disappointment in a given president. Using data from five original surveys, the authors confirm that the expectations gap is manifest in public opinion. It leads to lower approval ratings, lowers the chance that a president will be reelected, and even contributes to the success of the political party that does not hold the White House in congressional midterm elections. This study provides important insights not only on the American presidency and public opinion, but also on citizens' trust in government"--cProvided by publisher.  aDescription based on information from the publisher. 0aPresidentszUnited StatesxPublic opinion. 0aUnited StatesxPolitics and government. 4aElectronic books.1 aSilva, Carol L.1 aJenkins-Smith, Hank C.2 aMichigan Publishing (University of Michigan)epublisher.40zAccess to the Michigan Publishing online version:uhttps://doi.org/10